                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-331-off1864 t18260914-331-victim1757"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>FRANCIS LLOYD. On the 11th of July I was at the Haymarket Theatre, with my wife - the prisoner, as I believe, came up and requested me to let him get a coach, as is was raining; I would not; he then followed me up the <placeName id="t18260914-331-crimeloc1866">Haymarket</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-331-crimeloc1866" type="placeName" value="Haymarket"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-331-crimeloc1866" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-331-off1864 t18260914-331-crimeloc1866"></join>, and there were twenty or thirty persons; some one threw a stone, which staggered me a little; the prisoner then came and stood on my heel; I turned and said, "Is there not room enough on the flag-stones?" - I then put my hand to my pocket, but I had lost nothing - the prisoner then appeared to be inebriated, but I afterwards saw him follow some other persons up the Hay-market, and I said to the watchman, "There is a thief, I believe," and I was going away; but when I had got about thirty doors, Mrs. Lloyd put her hand to my pocket, and found that one shoe was gone from it; I put her into a shop, and went with the watchman; we took the prisoner with the shoe in his hand.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Why did not you give charge of him at once? A. I did not know that I had lost any thing; when he was taken he was speaking some flash words to a woman, who was very angry with him for not taking both shoes - one expression which I remarked was,"What a d-d fumbler he was not to get the two - one was of no use."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-331-person1758">
                  MICHAEL 
                  QUIN
               <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1758" type="surname" value="QUIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1758" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1758" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman of Coventry-street. I went with Lloyd, and took the prisoner with the shoe; he pretended to be drunk, but when he got to the watch-house he was perfectly sober.</p>
               <p>Prisoner to FRANCIS LLOYD. Q. Can you swear I took it out of your pocket at the time I trod on your heel? A. I can swear he got it out of my pocket, but I cannot say when.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-331-person1759">
                  GEORGE 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1759" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1759" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-331-person1759" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was night constable. The prisoner was brought to the watch-house with this shoe.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going along the Haymarket - a shoe was thrown at me, and I took it up.</p>
               <p>
